title: Introduction to NpsychBatteryNorms
text: Disclaimer R package started backbone visualization tool included R package NpsychAssessmentTool, quickly realized might use standalone tool researchers. therefore decided package important tools methods separately, resulted package. None implementations used commercial products standalone medical advice. Also note package distributed MIT Licence, meaning software provided “asis” authors liable claim, damages liabaility arising software. Also, note authors behind T-scores implemented test scores request scores edited, modified, translated otherwise part derivative work without prior written permission Mayo Clinic. use T-scores, contact Nikki Stricker /see Mayo Clinic Study Aging website data sharing.
code: # Install remotes if not already installed install.packages("remotes") remotes::install_github("rmtrane/NpsychBatteryNorms")

title: Introduction to NpsychBatteryNorms
text: main function package std_scores lets us standardize raw scores. example, can standardize raw score MoCA 21 57 year old male patient 15 years education using normative data published NACC: can standardize score using various methods. table showing methods implemented, use implemented_std_methods. shows method/ version combos available (1) (0): can also reverse lookup: variables can standardized using regression models published NACC: Standardizing using NACC published regression model, get slightly different normative score.
code: library(NpsychBatteryNorms)  std_scores(   raw_scores = 21,   var_name = "MOCATOTS",   sex = "m",   age = 57,   education = 15,   method = "norms",   version = "nacc" ) #> [1] -2.192308 std_methods(var_name = "MOCATOTS") #>       method         version available #> 1      norms            nacc         1 #> 2      norms         updated         1 #> 3      norms    ravlt_trials         0 #> 4 regression            nacc         1 #> 5 regression     nacc_legacy         0 #> 6 regression updated_2024.06         1 #> 7 regression updated_2025.06         1 #> 8    T-score            <NA>         0 std_methods(method = "regression", version = "nacc") #>  [1] "MOCATOTS"  "CRAFTVRS"  "CRAFTURS"  "UDSBENTC"  "DIGFORCT"  "DIGFORSL"  #>  [7] "DIGBACCT"  "DIGBACLS"  "ANIMALS"   "VEG"       "TRAILA"    "TRAILB"    #> [13] "CRAFTDVR"  "CRAFTDRE"  "CRAFTCUE"  "UDSBENTD"  "UDSBENRS"  "MINTTOTS"  #> [19] "MINTTOTW"  "MINTSCNG"  "MINTPCNG"  "UDSVERFC"  "UDSVERLC"  "UDSVERTN"  #> [25] "UDSVERTE"  "UDSVERTI"  "trailaadj" "trailbadj" std_scores(   raw_scores = 21,   var_name = "MOCATOTS",   sex = "m",   age = 57,   education = 15,   method = "regression",   version = "nacc" ) #> [1] -2.324629

title: Introduction to NpsychBatteryNorms

title: Calculate normative scores for neuropsychological test scores
text: main function package std_scores lets us standardize raw scores. example, can standardize raw score MoCA 21 57 year old male patient 15 years education using normative data published NACC: details, see Get started page
code: library(NpsychBatteryNorms)  std_scores(   raw_scores = 21,   var_name = "MOCATOTS",   sex = "m",   age = 57,   education = 15,   method = "norms",   version = "nacc" ) [1] -2.192308

what: Calcaulate Functional Assessment Score summary — calculate_fas
title: Calcaulate Functional Assessment Score summary — calculate_fas
text: Calculates Functional Assessment Score summary (FAS) ten scores bills taxes shopping games stove meal prep events paying attention remembering appointments travel score scale 0 (Normal), 1 (difficulty, self), 2 (Requires assistance), 3 (dependent). , error codes 8 (applicable, e.g. never ) 9 (Unknown) also allowed, -4 indicates data collected. FAS calculated sum ten scores 8s 9s counted 0.

title: Calcaulate Functional Assessment Score summary — calculate_fas
code: calculate_fas(   BILLS,   TAXES,   SHOPPING,   GAMES,   STOVE,   MEALPREP,   EVENTS,   PAYATTN,   REMDATES,   TRAVEL )

title: Calcaulate Functional Assessment Score summary — calculate_fas
text: BILLS score ability write checks, pay bills, balancing check book. TAXES score ability assemble tax records, business affairs, papers. SHOPPING score shopping alone clothes, household necessities, groceries. GAMES score playing game skill bridge chess, working hobby STOVE score ability heat water, make cup coffee, turn stove MEALPREP score ability prepare balanced meal EVENTS score keeping track current events PAYATTN score ability pay attention understand TV program, book, magazine REMDATES score remembering appointments, family occasions, holidays, medications. TRAVEL score traveling neighborhood, driving, arranging take public transportation

title: Standardize Raw Cognitive Scores using Regression Models — std_scores_using_regression
text: general, standardize scores subtracting estimate (possibly conditional) expected value variable considered, divide difference estimate (possibly conditional) standard deviation. aim using regression model adjusts age, sex, years education, find conditional expected value $$ \mu = \beta_0 + \beta_{age} \cdot \verb|age| + \beta_{education} \cdot \verb|education| + \beta_{sex} \cdot \verb|sex| $$ \(\verb|sex|\) \(1\) patient female, \(0\) otherwise. std_scores_using_regression takes coefficients named vector \(\verb|c(intercept = |\beta_0\verb|, age = |\beta_{age}\verb|, education = |\beta_{education}\verb|, sex = |\beta_{sex}\verb|)|\). normative score given \(\verb|(raw_scores - |\mu\verb|)/sd|\), sd estimated standard deviation passed sd argument. typically root mean squared error (RMSE) linear regression model. One final caveat: consistency, "flip sign" normative scores higher raw score values correspond worse performance. case trail making scores (written oral) related time number errors.
